WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Our first speaker for this afternoon will be Dewey Dunnington.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:22.200
Hi, this is a lot of people, this is great.

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:25.440
So I'm here today to talk to you about programming with ggplot2.

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:30.360
I imagine that all of you use ggplot2, or many of you use ggplot2.

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:34.480
It's a fantastic package for making graphics, and a lot of times, there are times you need

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:39.919
to do that in a function, or in a Shiny app, or in a parameterized report, or in a package.

00:00:39.919 --> 00:00:45.639
And those are all great uses of ggplot2, and there's some different paradigms around how

00:00:45.639 --> 00:00:48.840
to do that, and I just wanted to talk about that.

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:54.320
So my story starts, as many great books and movies have started, with the reverse dependency

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:55.320
check.

00:00:55.320 --> 00:01:00.799
So reverse dependency checks are something that the ggplot2 team does when we release,

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:05.919
or we're preparing a release for ggplot, and there's over 1,500 packages that directly

00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:12.519
import or depend on ggplot2, and over 2,500 that use it in the suggests on a package.

00:01:12.519 --> 00:01:16.599
So there's a lot of ggplot code on CRAN.

00:01:16.599 --> 00:01:22.000
And that's great for us because it means that there are a lot of use cases that are considered

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.919
that we didn't actually know about necessarily.

00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:29.760
So we run all of the command checks with the old version of the package, and command checks

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:34.559
with the new version of the package, and see which packages broke.

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:40.239
And sometimes that's our fault, and sometimes there are some things in other packages, but

00:01:40.239 --> 00:01:45.559
for the most part, as a fresh ggplot2 intern over the summer, it was my job to go through

00:01:45.559 --> 00:01:48.400
all of the packages that we broke.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:53.320
And through doing that, I was able to read a lot of ggplot2 code and realize that there

00:01:53.320 --> 00:01:59.800
were a lot of problems that people were trying to solve in packages that we hadn't ever documented,

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:03.279
and also in some cases that we hadn't made possible.

00:02:03.279 --> 00:02:08.119
And so the result of that was this vignette using ggplot2 in packages.

00:02:08.119 --> 00:02:13.919
It's available on the development version of the ggplot2 package down site, the main

00:02:13.919 --> 00:02:21.639
site for ggplot2, and the release of ggplot2, the next version is coming, I'm told, and

00:02:21.639 --> 00:02:24.720
then it will be on the main ggplot2 website.

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:29.639
But this talk is largely derived from that, and so I'd encourage you to read it if you'd

00:02:29.639 --> 00:02:32.559
like to know more.

00:02:32.559 --> 00:02:37.160
So I'm gonna start with something much like the ggplot that is an R for data science.

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:41.520
This is one of the first plots that many people make in R, and if not the first R code that

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:42.520
they ever type.

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:48.000
But this is using the mpg package, it's a bunch of cars, and so my 2008 Ford Ranger

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.240
was a four-wheel drive car, and it had a huge engine and terrible gas mileage, and

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:55.520
so it's down here.

00:02:55.520 --> 00:03:01.360
My Crosstrek that I currently drive is up here somewhere, smaller engine, better gas

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:08.199
mileage, and the 80cc scooter that I sometimes drive is off the chart and off the chart.

00:03:08.199 --> 00:03:12.080
Excellent gas mileage, very small engine, sounds like a lawnmower.

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:14.960
So that's what we're looking at here, and there's a couple things, this is a good plot

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:20.759
just to illustrate some of the problems that I noticed where people were trying to solve.

00:03:20.759 --> 00:03:24.399
So for a variety of reasons, you might start out with something like this.

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:28.639
Maybe it's a parameterized report, so you've got something in our markdown, you've set

00:03:28.639 --> 00:03:33.839
it up so that you can change what the color variable might be, like maybe you don't want

00:03:33.839 --> 00:03:37.360
it to be the class of the car, maybe you want it to be something else.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:41.880
And also you might want to change how the points are grouped in facets.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:45.960
And so you have a facet variable, in this case we're using the DRV variable, whether

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:50.000
it's four-wheel drive, front-wheel drive, that kind of thing.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:57.559
But we have this mapping and facet specification that uses tidy evaluation, so ggplot knows

00:03:57.559 --> 00:04:04.039
that class, for example, is to look for it in the mpg dataset, because that's the plot

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:11.520
data, and it knows to look for the DRV variable in mpg because that's the plot data, but you

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:18.079
can't just, if you put a string in there, it won't do what you expect it to do.

00:04:18.079 --> 00:04:23.640
So the best way, I think, to solve this problem is to use the dot data pronoun to do that.

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:31.399
And pronoun is a fancy word for the fact that ggplot now knows that dot data is a stand-in

00:04:31.399 --> 00:04:36.839
for mpg, so it's a stand-in for the layer data, for the plot data, and so you can specify

00:04:36.839 --> 00:04:39.720
these things and use them much like you would a data frame.

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:43.679
You can subset them with the double brackets, you can use the dollar sign, which I'll show

00:04:43.679 --> 00:04:51.079
a bit later, and you can do that both with a facet specification and with a mapping.

00:04:51.079 --> 00:04:57.200
So this is really powerful, and this lets us use syntax that we sort of expect in a

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:02.200
mapping and in a facet specification.

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:06.040
So then you can make a function around it, and this isn't artificial, by the way, this

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:10.200
is actually how I made this, this is the process that I go through when I make a function

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:15.679
for ggplot, so the order is kind of helpful, I think.

00:05:15.679 --> 00:05:21.880
So you can put it in a function, we can pass color variable in as arguments, and then we

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:25.320
can call that function and we get a plot.

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:31.000
So that's a useful way to simplify making possibly a bunch of plots or making plots

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.480
in our markdown report.

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:38.040
So we've got this function now, it's got some arguments, those arguments are what we expect

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:40.239
them to be.

00:05:40.239 --> 00:05:44.519
But it doesn't quite work because we actually can't remove the color mapping.

00:05:44.519 --> 00:05:49.279
So if we go back to this plot, what if we don't actually want color in there?

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:52.000
And there's lots of reasons that you might want to do that, you've got a checkbox in

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:59.720
a Shiny app or in a parameterized report, you want it to not make things colored.

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:01.399
So currently that doesn't work.

00:06:01.399 --> 00:06:05.859
So we have to go back to the code and change some things.

00:06:05.859 --> 00:06:10.880
So the best way I think to solve this problem is to take this mapping here, so this is what

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:13.359
we're doing with the mapping, and just move that up.

00:06:13.359 --> 00:06:19.200
So we can't modify it if it's not on its own, and it's a bit simpler to bring it up top

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:25.359
so we don't have to modify it within the geom point function, it's a bit cleaner to read.

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:31.119
And then we can test for if the color variable is null, and then we can modify the mapping

00:06:31.119 --> 00:06:33.239
based on that.

00:06:33.239 --> 00:06:36.720
And so this is a pretty common problem that I've had personally with programming with

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:37.720
ggplot2.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:42.279
And so I think it's a good pattern where you put your mapping up top, and you can modify

00:06:42.279 --> 00:06:47.839
that as you go depending on what you're trying to do.

00:06:47.839 --> 00:06:51.760
So that's all well and good, but we still can't remove the facet.

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:57.200
So we've got three panels, and maybe we don't actually want any panels.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:02.079
Maybe we want to give a user of a Shiny app an option to say, okay, don't actually group

00:07:02.079 --> 00:07:08.920
this by anything, maybe we just would like to have just one plot.

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:12.720
So again, back to our code.

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:16.959
And I think that the best way to solve this problem is to, the facet was previously at

00:07:16.959 --> 00:07:18.880
the bottom, and it's just to move that up a little bit.

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:23.320
So again, we can work with it a bit easier, and we can keep the structure of the plot

00:07:23.320 --> 00:07:28.559
at the bottom of the function so that it stays clear exactly what the plot is made

00:07:28.559 --> 00:07:29.559
up of.

00:07:29.559 --> 00:07:34.600
And then we can test whether the facet variable is null.

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:38.799
And we can use this trick with ggplot2, which I think is highly underused, where you can

00:07:38.799 --> 00:07:43.600
add null to a ggplot2, and it changes nothing.

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:47.179
And you think that that's not actually that useful, but it's really useful in a situation

00:07:47.179 --> 00:07:52.220
like this, because without it, you would have to define two ggplots.

00:07:52.220 --> 00:07:55.420
You wouldn't be able to just say, okay, I don't want to add anything to the plot in

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:56.739
a certain case.

00:07:56.739 --> 00:08:02.019
So I think this conditional adding of possibly nothing to a plot is really powerful, and

00:08:02.019 --> 00:08:06.500
it really helps clean up your actual ggplot specification.

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:11.899
So that interns like me, when I'm reading your code, it's a bit easier to read.

00:08:11.899 --> 00:08:12.899
But mostly for you.

00:08:12.899 --> 00:08:14.579
It's mostly for you.

00:08:14.579 --> 00:08:17.940
So now we've successfully have a slightly less interesting plot.

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:22.380
But the point is we can actually modify now a couple of different options about it.

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:29.339
We could add the color back in if we wanted to, and it still wouldn't give us any panels.

00:08:29.339 --> 00:08:35.099
So I think that the big take-homes here for just using ggplot in a function is that you

00:08:35.099 --> 00:08:39.780
can use .data much like a data frame within AES.

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:44.619
So you can use it as a stand-in for that layer data that you want to map.

00:08:44.619 --> 00:08:49.539
And it follows all the regular rules within the double brackets so that you can put variable

00:08:49.539 --> 00:08:55.380
names in there that might be inputs in a Shiny app or they might be parameterized report

00:08:55.380 --> 00:08:59.340
variables or even just in a function that you made for yourself because you want to

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:02.739
make a whole lot of plots.

00:09:02.739 --> 00:09:05.619
That works both in AES and VARs.

00:09:05.619 --> 00:09:11.820
The second thing that I think is really helpful for just using ggplot in a function is using

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:16.179
the fact that adding null to the end of a ggplot does nothing.

00:09:16.179 --> 00:09:19.539
And that's really helpful if you might want to add something and you might not.

00:09:19.539 --> 00:09:24.580
It helps keep your actual specification of a ggplot pretty clean.

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:29.780
And something that I didn't show an example of but that's similarly useful is that you

00:09:29.780 --> 00:09:36.520
can add a list of things to a ggplot and it will add all of them in the list sequentially.

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:37.520
So that's pretty useful.

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:42.799
It's a bit easier to programmatically modify lists than to programmatically modify adding

00:09:42.799 --> 00:09:45.599
a bunch of things together.

00:09:45.599 --> 00:09:50.559
So that's another nice trick that you might be able to use in specifying some of your

00:09:50.559 --> 00:09:53.280
plots.

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:58.960
So if you are just making a function, then that's as far as you need to go.

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:03.840
But if you want to use ggplot2 in a package, there are some other steps that you need to

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:04.840
take.

00:10:04.840 --> 00:10:06.979
There's lots of reasons that you might want to make a little package.

00:10:06.979 --> 00:10:10.739
Maybe you'd like to put it on GitHub and let your friends install it.

00:10:10.739 --> 00:10:14.260
Or maybe you want to submit it to CRAN.

00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:16.859
So there's a couple more constraints that come with that.

00:10:16.859 --> 00:10:19.619
So this is the plot mpg package.

00:10:19.619 --> 00:10:22.780
I'll show you a link to the slides at the end of the talk and you can see this little

00:10:22.780 --> 00:10:23.780
tiny package.

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:27.539
It has one function, the plot mpg function.

00:10:27.539 --> 00:10:33.979
And it lets you specify a color mapping and it lets you specify a facet variable.

00:10:33.979 --> 00:10:36.179
So that's what it looks like.

00:10:36.179 --> 00:10:37.179
And if we start...

00:10:37.179 --> 00:10:38.179
Oh, sorry.

00:10:38.179 --> 00:10:41.179
Very important digression.

00:10:41.179 --> 00:10:42.179
I didn't...

00:10:42.179 --> 00:10:43.700
This slide isn't in there because of any of your functions.

00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:45.419
Your functions are fantastic.

00:10:45.419 --> 00:10:51.219
This slide is in there because recently when I was making this talk, I was faced with about

00:10:51.219 --> 00:10:56.780
400 lines of conditional plotting code that I put in a package for ggplot2.

00:10:56.780 --> 00:10:57.780
Lots of if statements.

00:10:57.780 --> 00:11:03.460
I was trying to make the perfect plot for plotting this very particular type of data

00:11:03.460 --> 00:11:05.820
about mud, because that's what I do.

00:11:06.460 --> 00:11:12.020
And what I realized when I was going through this code is that really what it boiled down

00:11:12.020 --> 00:11:14.900
to was four lines of a ggplot.

00:11:14.900 --> 00:11:20.820
There was really four lines of ggplot code that took hundreds of lines to handle all

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:24.940
of the edge cases about various types of data that could end up there.

00:11:24.940 --> 00:11:30.419
And so my solution to that was actually to make a vignette first and also to put examples

00:11:30.419 --> 00:11:34.780
in a really, really good data generating function.

00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:39.900
So what that ended up with is actually really good documentation, and I don't think that

00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:44.419
there was anybody that could make any less good plots.

00:11:44.419 --> 00:11:48.419
I think that it actually resulted in a far better package, and it was a lot easier for

00:11:48.419 --> 00:11:52.900
me to test, because I had this really great data generating function.

00:11:52.900 --> 00:11:54.900
So I think it's worth considering that.

00:11:54.900 --> 00:12:00.460
And even if you still would like a plot function, and you probably would still like a plot function,

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:07.219
if you do both of those things, then you can make something that's easier to test.

00:12:07.219 --> 00:12:10.380
So this is the function that we started with.

00:12:10.380 --> 00:12:15.460
So this is a great function, but it won't work necessarily in a package.

00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:20.099
So when you refer to anything in a package, you have to be really explicit about where

00:12:20.099 --> 00:12:21.179
it comes from.

00:12:21.179 --> 00:12:23.179
And I know that many of you probably know this.

00:12:23.179 --> 00:12:29.700
It's general package development, but you can use the colon colon to refer to something

00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:31.419
in a really particular package.

00:12:31.419 --> 00:12:37.659
But you can also do this thing where you import from ggplot2, and you can import those functions

00:12:37.659 --> 00:12:43.260
to use them within your package without having to do the ggplot2 colon colon thing.

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:44.900
Sometimes you do have to do that with datasets.

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:50.099
You always have to preface it with the package name beforehand.

00:12:50.099 --> 00:12:53.900
But this is a really great trick that you can use within a package to keep your code

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:54.900
looking clean.

00:12:54.900 --> 00:13:00.219
And if you use ggplot2 a lot, then this will keep your ggplot2 looking really clean inside

00:13:00.219 --> 00:13:02.940
the package and a lot easier to read.

00:13:02.940 --> 00:13:04.500
Again, I was an intern.

00:13:04.500 --> 00:13:05.859
I read a lot of code.

00:13:05.859 --> 00:13:11.099
And in the 400 lines of code that I just removed, ggplot2 colon colon, I did a search before

00:13:11.099 --> 00:13:12.099
I did it.

00:13:12.099 --> 00:13:15.580
It showed up, like, 157 times.

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:17.539
So this is a way to keep it a little bit cleaner.

00:13:17.539 --> 00:13:22.859
And then when you run the documentation, it will spit that into your namespace, and you

00:13:22.859 --> 00:13:28.099
can keep your code very similar to what it was before.

00:13:28.099 --> 00:13:29.179
But we're gonna get a problem.

00:13:29.179 --> 00:13:34.059
So I don't know if you guys have experienced this, but when I get a little X at the bottom

00:13:34.059 --> 00:13:43.099
of an R command check, my heart races a little bit, and I start to question my existence.

00:13:43.099 --> 00:13:46.979
But in this case, we're getting three errors that don't actually affect whether the function

00:13:46.979 --> 00:13:49.179
works or not.

00:13:49.179 --> 00:13:52.979
But there's something that R doesn't know about the function that we have to tell it

00:13:52.979 --> 00:13:54.260
explicitly.

00:13:54.260 --> 00:13:58.739
So in this case, we've got three things that R thinks that aren't defined.

00:13:58.739 --> 00:14:04.179
So if you're following along, there's this displacement variable, this highway variable,

00:14:04.179 --> 00:14:06.059
and the dot data variable.

00:14:06.059 --> 00:14:10.940
So these are things that R very correctly has not detected in some assigned statement

00:14:10.940 --> 00:14:14.059
before that.

00:14:14.059 --> 00:14:19.739
And ggplot2 is smart enough to know that these things are in your layer data, but R

00:14:19.739 --> 00:14:20.739
doesn't know that.

00:14:20.739 --> 00:14:25.099
So we can explicitly tell it that using the dot data pronoun again.

00:14:25.099 --> 00:14:30.780
So this is the new and improved code, where we're using dot data as something like a data

00:14:30.780 --> 00:14:38.260
frame that we can use the dollar sign to extract a variable out of it, and that will help with

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:39.260
the...

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:41.460
Or that will remove the command check note.

00:14:41.460 --> 00:14:42.460
So we also...

00:14:42.460 --> 00:14:46.539
You'll notice that I had to import from our laying dot data.

00:14:46.539 --> 00:14:51.179
Dot data, we can't do that with, because it's special within the mapping.

00:14:51.179 --> 00:14:55.979
But if we do this, then it will make that problem go away, and so we'll get that little

00:14:55.979 --> 00:15:04.020
check note to disappear, and your heart can fill with joy when you run the R command check.

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:07.140
So a final thing that I want to talk about is testing.

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:12.580
So if you followed my advice earlier and made a really, really good data generating

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:18.299
function, so a function that returned a data frame that you can pass directly into ggplot2,

00:15:18.299 --> 00:15:21.340
then you can test that reasonably well.

00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:26.619
And if you saw Jenny Bryan's talk this morning, you had a little test that introduction.

00:15:26.619 --> 00:15:31.700
And you can use something called vdiffer, which is a package by Leonel Henry, part of

00:15:31.700 --> 00:15:36.119
the Tidyverse team, to actually test the visual output.

00:15:36.119 --> 00:15:41.200
So you can't always test something programmatically, and a lot of times with a plot, you shouldn't.

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:44.820
You shouldn't reach into a plot object and try and test something.

00:15:44.820 --> 00:15:49.719
It's much better, and it's much more realistic, honestly, to the end point, to test the image

00:15:49.719 --> 00:15:51.440
that got generated.

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:57.059
So in ggplot2, we use this, and I think there are hundreds of plots that we have to check.

00:15:57.059 --> 00:16:00.320
And if we had to do that manually, we might not do them, or we might not do it as well,

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:02.099
or we might miss something.

00:16:02.099 --> 00:16:05.840
So we use the vdiffer package to generate some version of record for every single one

00:16:05.840 --> 00:16:07.200
of those figures.

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:12.479
And then when we run the test, it checks that every single one of those figures is identical.

00:16:12.479 --> 00:16:17.479
So you can use it much like another expectation, where we have this expect doppelganger, where

00:16:17.479 --> 00:16:23.880
we're expecting this plot mpg function, as it's called, to generate the same thing as

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:27.200
some version we have on file.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:31.359
And so you can make the version on file by running this little function in the vdiffer

00:16:31.359 --> 00:16:37.960
package, and that will run all of your tests, collect all the doppelgangers, and spit out

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:42.599
something that looks like this, where any of your new cases, it will ask you to validate.

00:16:42.599 --> 00:16:45.840
So it will say, yes, this is the version that I want on file.

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:49.880
But if any of them are mismatched, it will also show you the two versions, so you can

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:51.919
see what changed.

00:16:51.919 --> 00:16:56.080
So whether that's a change in your code that induced a change in a figure, or whether it's

00:16:56.080 --> 00:17:00.760
a change in our code and ggplot2's code that induced a change in your figure, you can see

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:05.479
what the change was, and whether or not that is something that is meaningful to you, in

00:17:05.479 --> 00:17:09.280
which case you can tell us or change your code, or whether it's something that is so

00:17:09.280 --> 00:17:15.119
small that it doesn't matter to you, and then you can generate a new version of record.

00:17:15.119 --> 00:17:20.239
So I think that that is a really powerful tool, and it's something that I've just started

00:17:20.239 --> 00:17:23.079
to move any package that I do to use.

00:17:23.079 --> 00:17:30.319
It doesn't have to be ggplot2, it can do lots of other formats, and it's a fantastic package.

00:17:30.319 --> 00:17:35.959
So using ggplot2 in a package, we can use the double colon that you might be familiar

00:17:35.959 --> 00:17:41.079
with to refer to objects in ggplot2, whether they're functions or datasets.

00:17:41.079 --> 00:17:44.599
And then we can also use this import from syntax.

00:17:44.599 --> 00:17:48.800
So we can actually import specific functions from ggplot2 so that we don't have to use

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:54.880
ggplot2 colon colon, so that your first line doesn't have to be ggplot2 colon colon, opening

00:17:54.880 --> 00:18:02.160
parentheses, ggplot2 colon colon, aes, opening parentheses, it gets very dirty very quick.

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:08.439
The second is we can use the dot data within a mapping or a facet spec.

00:18:08.439 --> 00:18:16.380
We can use that to avoid command check problems with a variable not being defined.

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:18.239
And finally, you can test.

00:18:18.239 --> 00:18:19.239
Everyone should be testing.

00:18:19.239 --> 00:18:20.239
We love testing.

00:18:20.239 --> 00:18:23.760
And you can test graphical output using the vdiffer package.

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:26.319
And so this is a bit of a toy example that I did.

00:18:26.319 --> 00:18:28.079
It's the mpg dataset.

00:18:28.079 --> 00:18:32.199
There's a reason that there's not a plot mpg package, because people don't need help plotting

00:18:32.199 --> 00:18:34.479
that dataset.

00:18:34.479 --> 00:18:38.839
But you might need help plotting all of the Canadian election results starting in 1867.

00:18:38.839 --> 00:18:42.280
So this is something I did right after the Canadian election.

00:18:42.280 --> 00:18:44.119
We do have elections.

00:18:44.119 --> 00:18:47.000
But even though we're ruled by the queen, very technically.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.920
But this is every election since 1867.

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:53.300
And as you might imagine, it's pretty useful to have a plot function for that.

00:18:53.839 --> 00:18:56.020
And it's useful to have a data generating function.

00:18:56.020 --> 00:18:59.579
And there's a number of other problems that this package solves that I didn't have time

00:18:59.579 --> 00:19:01.099
to go into in the talk.

00:19:01.099 --> 00:19:02.939
And so if you're interested, I'd encourage you to check it out.

00:19:02.939 --> 00:19:05.859
It's a fairly minimal package.

00:19:05.859 --> 00:19:10.900
And I'd be happy to have any questions if you look at it and would like to ask me about

00:19:10.900 --> 00:19:12.699
them.

00:19:12.699 --> 00:19:13.699
So that is all I had.

00:19:13.699 --> 00:19:16.380
I'd encourage you to check out the vignette if this is something that you think you're

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:18.099
going to do a lot.

00:19:18.099 --> 00:19:24.300
And I'm also very happy to answer any questions now or later on GitHub or on Twitter or any

00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:25.300
one of the things.

00:19:25.300 --> 00:19:26.300
So thank you.

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:38.739
So we have maybe two minutes for a couple of quick questions, if you're amenable.

00:19:38.739 --> 00:19:39.739
Okay.

00:19:39.739 --> 00:19:40.739
Great.

00:19:40.739 --> 00:19:46.020
So it looks like a number of people in the audience were interested in your use of variable

00:19:46.020 --> 00:19:52.699
quoting and maybe why not or what about tidy eval.

00:19:52.699 --> 00:19:53.699
Yeah.

00:19:53.699 --> 00:19:54.699
Sure.

00:19:54.699 --> 00:19:56.780
So what I talked about is tidy eval.

00:19:56.780 --> 00:20:00.260
The dot data pronoun is tidy eval.

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:04.819
But if you're talking about the double braces or whether you're talking about the double

00:20:04.819 --> 00:20:10.300
exclamation point, those are things that you can use if you want your functions to use

00:20:10.300 --> 00:20:12.579
the same tidy evaluation semantics.

00:20:12.579 --> 00:20:14.199
A lot of times you actually don't want that.

00:20:14.199 --> 00:20:19.199
You don't actually want your function to do something nonstandard because a lot of

00:20:19.199 --> 00:20:21.160
people don't expect that.

00:20:21.160 --> 00:20:24.060
So I think that there are a lot of things that are good about that, and there's a lot

00:20:24.060 --> 00:20:26.660
of really great material by Hadley and others.

00:20:26.660 --> 00:20:31.079
But this is one of the ways that you can, if you don't happen to do that, that you can

00:20:31.079 --> 00:20:33.280
make that happen.

00:20:33.280 --> 00:20:35.400
Awesome.

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:36.400
Another question here.

00:20:36.400 --> 00:20:40.760
Could you explain the difference between using null and geom blank?

00:20:40.760 --> 00:20:41.920
Sure.

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:46.400
So you can use geom blank, but geom blank actually does do something.

00:20:46.400 --> 00:20:51.800
Geom blank will still make the limits of the axis do something.

00:20:51.800 --> 00:20:55.119
And so that's why I was adding null.

00:20:55.119 --> 00:20:58.839
So this is a geometry, and geom blank is a perfectly good way, or it might be, to do

00:20:58.839 --> 00:21:00.500
what you want to do.

00:21:00.500 --> 00:21:05.020
But if you have a scale that you might want to add or might not, then there is no scale

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:06.359
blank.

00:21:06.359 --> 00:21:08.959
So null is a stand-in for anything blank.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.000
It's just like that piece of the plot never happened.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:13.000
Awesome.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:17.319
I have maybe one more here, and I'm not sure if you'll understand or if you'll need more

00:21:17.319 --> 00:21:22.319
context, but how do you address the test brittleness when using vDiffer?

00:21:22.319 --> 00:21:23.959
Sorry, the test brittleness?

00:21:23.959 --> 00:21:24.959
Brittleness.

00:21:24.959 --> 00:21:25.959
Brittleness.

00:21:25.959 --> 00:21:26.959
Yeah.

00:21:26.959 --> 00:21:32.599
Yeah, so there's a lot of great material on vDiffer as a monitoring tool and not necessarily

00:21:32.599 --> 00:21:33.839
a testing tool.

00:21:33.839 --> 00:21:35.160
So it's sort of designed to be brittle.

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:39.640
It's designed to fail very easily when there's any little tiny change, because it really

00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:43.040
does check the SVG that was printed out.

00:21:43.040 --> 00:21:46.180
When I was rewriting the axes, I ran into a problem where I drew the tick marks in the

00:21:46.180 --> 00:21:48.839
opposite direction, and it detected that.

00:21:48.839 --> 00:21:51.160
And that is a good thing from our perspective.

00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:55.000
So by default, it doesn't run those tests on CRAN, so you don't have to worry about

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:59.479
your package failing on CRAN because of that, but it does run them on Travis if you're using

00:21:59.479 --> 00:22:03.199
Travis by default, and that is actually really helpful to make sure that your figures aren't

00:22:03.199 --> 00:22:05.400
different on some other operating system.

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:08.439
So it is brittle, but I think it's brittle by design, and I think that that is a good

00:22:08.439 --> 00:22:09.439
thing.

00:22:09.439 --> 00:22:12.520
There are some ways to get around not running it on certain platforms if you think that

00:22:12.520 --> 00:22:14.079
that's a problem.

00:22:14.079 --> 00:22:16.959
So I think it's still worth doing.

00:22:16.959 --> 00:22:17.959
Awesome.

00:22:17.959 --> 00:22:18.959
Thank you so much, Dewey.

00:22:18.959 --> 00:22:19.959
Please join me in in thanking Dewey one more time.

00:22:19.959 --> 00:22:20.959
Thank you.

00:22:20.959 --> 00:22:20.959


